<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-342-690  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 342 690.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Newsbytes  April 12 1990* Full Text COPYRIGHT Newsbytes Inc. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Moscow: bid awarded for computerized voting system in Perm.andO;(Dzerzhinsky Industrial Association wins contract with SupremeSoviet )</TITLE><AUTHOR>Tchashchin, Kirill.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   Dzerzhinsky Industrial Association (contracts).andO;Topic:     Soviet UnionSoviet Union. Supreme SovietAutomationGovernment ContractsGovernment AgencyPolitics.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>MOSCOW: BID AWARDED FOR COMPUTERIZED VOTING SYSTEM IN PERM MOSCOW, U.S.S.R.,andO;1990 APR 8 (NB) -- According to several newspapers, the Perm-basedDzerzhinsky Industrial Association has won a competition to set up anelectronic voting system for the Russian republic's Supreme Soviet(Parliament).andM;Perm, 1500 kilometers east of Moscow in the Ural region, is an industrialcity with over a million people.andM;The association's chief executive told Newsbytes that his organization'ssystem won the competition since it was already developed while others werestill collecting data on how to build theirs.andM;The multifunctional system, capable of serving over 8,000 people votingsimultaneously, is designed only with Soviet-made chips so maintenance willcause no currency expenses for the Russian Republic's parliament.andM;The official green light to start construction was given by Parliament.andP;  Thesystem will be completely installed and tested in the middle of May.andM;West Germany-based Phillips was given a licence to build similar system forthe USSR Parliament's 5,000-person meetings.andM;(Kirill Tchashchin/19900410)</TEXT></DOC>